```cpp
#include <SPI.h>
#include <nRF24L01.h>
#include <RF24.h>

// nRF24L01+ control pins
RF24 radio(3, 2);  // CE = D3, CSN = D2

// Reading pipe address — must match the transmitter
const byte address[6] = "00001";

void setup() {
  // Initialize the radio
  radio.begin();

  // Open reading pipe 0 with the shared address
  radio.openReadingPipe(0, address);

  // Disable Auto-Acknowledgment (receiver doesn't send ACK packets back)
  radio.setAutoAck(false);

  // Set data rate to 250kbps — longest range, most reliable
  radio.setDataRate(RF24_250KBPS);

  // Set PA level to LOW — sufficient for RC control, saves power
  radio.setPALevel(RF24_PA_LOW);

  // Set channel (optional — default is 76, but can be changed)
  // radio.setChannel(108);  // Uncomment to change from default

  // Enter primary receiver mode (PRX)
  radio.startListening();

  // At this point the radio is actively listening on pipe 0
  // for packets addressed to "00001"
}
```

Key points:
1. **`RF24 radio(3, 2)`**: The constructor takes CE pin first, CSN pin second. D3 = CE (Chip Enable — controls TX/RX mode), D2 = CSN (Chip Select Not — SPI slave select).
2. **`radio.begin()`**: Initializes the SPI communication with the nRF24L01+ module. Must be called before any other RF24 methods.
3. **`radio.openReadingPipe(0, address)`**: Opens data pipe 0 for receiving. The 5-byte address `"00001"` must match exactly what the transmitter uses for its writing pipe. Pipe 0 is the only pipe that can receive auto-ACK payloads, though auto-ACK is disabled here.
4. **`radio.setAutoAck(false)`**: Disables automatic acknowledgment packets. In a unidirectional RC control scenario (transmitter → receiver), the receiver doesn't need to send ACKs back. This simplifies the protocol and reduces airtime congestion.
5. **`radio.setDataRate(RF24_250KBPS)`**: Sets the over-the-air data rate to 250kbps. This is the slowest but most robust rate — it provides the longest range and best penetration through obstacles compared to 1Mbps or 2Mbps. For RC control where range matters more than throughput, 250kbps is the standard choice.
6. **`radio.setPALevel(RF24_PA_LOW)`**: Sets the Power Amplifier level to LOW. This reduces current consumption (~7mA vs ~11mA at higher PA levels) while still providing adequate range for typical RC operation. For longer-range applications, `RF24_PA_HIGH` can be used instead.
7. **`radio.startListening()`**: Switches the radio into Primary Receiver (PRX) mode. In this mode, the nRF24L01+ continuously monitors for incoming packets on the opened reading pipe. The `radio.available()` call in the main loop will return true when a valid packet arrives.

